      },
      "date": "2012-10-08 12:23:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nandreas, I'm actually not sure this is the right place for the change. I tend to think we should be able to tell mkfs.lustre do not mark filesystem a fresh one.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2ece9361c78e3721d1bcfedc884bfe13316b22c2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-10-08 14:40:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/2c767470-1151-11e2-9408-52540035b04c).  Ran 12 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "4e39fa7f3c10aee3feae8b36e719f600be95c377",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-10-08 15:49:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nIt isn't clear from the bug or commit comment what problem is being solved here. Having a bug report which describes the symptoms/error that is seen if the label is not set correctly.\n\nIf a user is doing a normal backup/restore process, they will not necessarily know to also reset the filesystem label, so this needs to be documented in the manual.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a9cb7b4f0660b2ca7f623a157435abe15046c366",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-10-08 16:01:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nmy bad .. please find a short description in http://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-2108",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "71429249264005bfd63328e117af0a9849d6000a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-10-09 09:31:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b30264b6214db5737828d89dc592bd5fed2c0acb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-10-09 09:33:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI consider this situation valid because in some specific cases cleanup can be called twice.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c767719dc5df232cf691c86d26a50248bb2ed52b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-10-09 09:37:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n.. which in turn let us simplify the code a bit so that in an error or shutdown path we call shutdown() and be ensured it's not forgotten in some rare cases.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "28615473eb93391b9aa3d0f0fe6dccd9e9c9ef40",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-10-09 09:51:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n\"LASSERT(dev->od_otable_it == NULL);\" means the otable-based iteration has already been stopped when shutdown. If it is triggered, then means someone forgot to stop the iteration before the shutdown, which is abnormal. and should be fixed. So for normal usages, as long as the iteration has been stopped, the osd_scrub_cleanup() can be called many times without trigger the assertion.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0a7697cad83211adc8bf8461f382bb7d7840e4ef",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-10-09 09:52:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nhm, right...",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
